    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Pro-Tips for Using the Webtigo Frequency Detector
    </h3>
    <ul style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li><strong>Find a Quiet Space:</strong> Microphones can get confused by background noise. If the TV is blaring
            while you are trying to tune a guitar, the detector might pick up the TV announcer's voice instead of your
            strings.</li>
        <li><strong>Get Close:</strong> Bring your phone or laptop microphone as close to the sound source as safely
            possible. This ensures the dominant frequency is loud and clear.</li>
        <li><strong>Sustain the Sound:</strong> Short, sharp noises (like clapping) contain a massive jumble of
            different frequencies. For the best reading, analyze continuous, sustained sounds like a hum, a whistle, a
            sung note, or a ringing bell.</li>
    </ul>

